{"id":"1808.01170","submitter":"Emmanuil Saridakis","authors":"Shreya Banerjee, Yi-Fu Cai and Emmanuel N. Saridakis","title":"Evading the theoretical no-go theorem for nonsingular bounces in\n  Horndeski/Galileon cosmology","comments":"9 pages, 5 figures, version published in Class.Quant.Grav","journal-ref":null,"doi":"10.1088/1361-6382/ab256a","report-no":null,"categories":"gr-qc astro-ph.CO hep-th","license":"http://arxiv.org/licenses/nonexclusive-distrib/1.0/","abstract":"  We show that a nonsingular bounce, free of ghosts and gradient instabilities,\ncan be realized in the framework of Horndeski or generalized Galileon\ncosmology. In particular, we first review that the theoretical no-go theorem,\nwhich states that the above is impossible, is based on two very strong\nassumptions, namely that a particular quantity cannot be discontinuous during\nthe bounce, and that there is only one bounce. However, as we show in the\npresent work, the first assumption not only can be violated in a general\nHorndeski/Galileon scenario, but also it is necessarily violated at the bounce\npoint within the subclass of Horndeski/Galileon gravity in which $K(\\phi,X)$\nbecomes zero at $X=0$. Additionally, concerning the second assumption, which is\ncrucial in improved versions of the theorem which claim that even if a\nnonlinear free of pathologies can be realized it will lead to pathologies in\nthe infinite past or infinite future, we show that if needed it can be evaded\nby considering cyclic cosmology, with an infinite sequence of nonsingular\nbounces free of pathologies, which forbids the universe to reach the\n\"problematic\" regime at infinite past or infinite future. Finally, in order to\nmake the analysis more transparent we provide explicit examples where\nnonsingular bounces without theoretical pathologies can be achieved.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Fri, 3 Aug 2018 12:09:33 GMT"},{"version":"v2","created":"Sat, 20 Oct 2018 10:10:17 GMT"},{"version":"v3","crea